    <article>
      <H3>Riot Games Collegiate Summit</H3>
      <h6>9/16/13</h6>
      <div class="large-6 columns">
        <p>Earlier this summer, E-Sports Initiative was selected as one of the prestigious 21 schools that would take part in the first annual Riot Games Collegiate Summit. My name is Jon Leung, and as the organizer in charge of League of Legends events at ESI, I was chosen to represent us at this event. </p>
        <p>The Collegiate Summit was an initiative brought up by Riot to bring together collegiate event organizers from all over North America to Riot’s headquarters in Santa Monica, California and discuss the future of League of Legends’ Collegiate Program. </p>
        </div>
        <div class="large-6 columns">
          <%=image_tag('riotArticle1.png')%>
        </div>
        <div class = "large-12 columns">
          <p>The summit was announced late June – just barely a month before the date of the summit, where 20 collegiate organizations across the United States and one from Canada were notified that one representative from each group would be receiving an all-expenses paid trip to Santa Monica. Needless to say, colleges across the continent were ecstatic at this invitation that came completely out of the blue. It was determined that the official days of the summit were to be July 25-26th, but Riot Games graciously provided flight and accommodations for us to stay from 24-28 so that we organizers would have some extra time to get to know each other, have fun, and also work on potential projects and collaborations.</p>
          <p>On the 24th of July, after spending hours in excitement during our respective flights to Santa Monica, I finally got the chance to meet many of the collegiate organizers that I had previously known only by their profile pictures from Facebook and Skype. It was an enlightening experience to talk to all these organizers and discover everyone’s huge variety of backgrounds and motivations. All of us were heavily involved in our respective organizations, but no two stories of how we got where we are were the same. After a long night bonding and getting to know each other while waiting for the last of the representatives to arrive, and finally returned to our rooms in excitement for the eventful days that awaited us.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="large-4 columns">
            <%=image_tag('riotArticle2.png')%>
          </div>
          <div class = "large-8 columns">
            <p>On the first day of the Summit we woke up early to get on our shuttle bus towards Riot’s HQ. where many of us got the chance to meet Steve “Jaws” Jaworski – Coordinator of the Collegiate Program, in person for the first time. We were asked to sign NDA’s regarding photographs and sensitive information that we would be shown, and were ushered into a function room where we had breakfast and got the chance to meet the founders of Riot Games and had a short Q and A session with them. Afterwards, we received a tour of Riot’s multi-floor office and got to meet many of the interesting personalities that brought us our favorite game.</p>
            <p>
              We then began our more work-related activities by meeting and receiving presentations from the many members of the Riot Community Team – some of which we had already been in contact with before through our past events. Many issues were covered regarding the past, present and future of the Collegiate Program, allowing us all to share our own experiences and ideas to better the system. 
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class = "large-12 columns">
            <p>As night came we were brought to the Riot in-house PC Bang (Internet Café), where we got the chance to unwind and get our League of Legends fix with fellow organizers, before finally returning to the hotel to rest for the many exciting events scheduled for next day. </p>
            <p>On the second day, we were given the chance to visit the studio where the League of Legends Championship Series (LCS) games are both played and streamed. Under NDA, I’m not allowed to disclose much information regarding the studio and their setups, but I must say that I was extremely impressed with the efficiency and production value that Riot’s small team manages to bring to the table.</p>
            <p>After our visit at the LCS studio, we returned to Riot HQ, where we set up to begin the Collegiate Town Hall Q and A Event. For this Town Hall, collegiate organizers across the nation tuned in and posted questions to both us lead coordinators and the Riot Community Team.  This 2-3 hour event was livestreamed on twitch and aimed to share the goals and experience of us more experienced organizers with some of the newer members of collegiate League of Legends.</p>
          </div>
          <div class = "large-6 columns">
            <p> Thanks to Riot Games, I was able to meet many other event organizers from across the continent and establish relationships and plans to bring League of Legends events and prizes to more and more students. The Collegiate Summit was a blast, and opened the door to collaboration with many more colleges and gamers. </p>
            <p>Stay tuned for updates and announcements for some of these aforementioned collaboration events in the near future!</p>
          </div>
          <div class = "large-6 columns">
            <%= image_tag('riotArticle3.png')%>
          </div>
        
      
    </article>


